author: Joe Zedalis | NJ Advance Media for NJ.com
title: 2016 District 20 recap: Raritan wins team title with balance, Perth Amboy's Torres is MOW
text:
Saturday's results, photos and more 
AT SOUTH BRUNSWICK 
TEAM CHAMPION : In a district where nine different teams had at least one champ, Raritan bulled its way to the team title with its balance. The Rockets had four firsts, two seconds and three, third-place finished. Raritan had 230.5 points and outscored Monroe (182.5), Holmdel (127.5) and Perth Amboy (101). Raritan received first-place efforts from Robert Taddeo (106), Charles Barrale (113), Russell Benson (132) and Ethan Wolf (220). 
MOST OUTSTANDING WRESTLER: Perth Amboy senior Norberto Torres won the 120-pound title and MOW honors. Torres, now 33-3, won by fall in the quarterfinals, by a 6-0 decision in the semifinals and then by a 15-1 major decision in the 120-pound final against Jaleel Gopaul of Matawan . Torres won his second district title. He was first at 113 in 2015 and second last year. 
BACK POINTS: It was a big day for Perth Amboy. Not only was Torres named the Outstanding Wrestler, retiring head coach Mike Giordano was named Coach of the Year and assitance coach Rob Morales Assistant Coach of the Year. Giordano, one of the most repsected coaches anywhere, led Perth Amboy to a 12-12 record and a Central Jersey playoff spot. Perth Amboy also received a title-winning effort from Joseph Pacheco at 106 pounds. ... Monroe 285-pounder Lou Ceres showed he was light on his feet, recording a 15-second pin in the final. ... Holmdel's rebuilding program went home with three champions -- Dean Gallo (138), Scott Dupont (152) and Chris Ammirati (160). ... Matawan's Derrick Wiley -- a three-sport star for the Huskies -- improved to 32-1 on his way to the 170-pound crown. ... Raritan's Russell Benson won his second district title. 
THREE-, FOUR-TIME CHAMPS : None.
